content.problemStatement:
- You've learned how to target and style specific elements, classes, and IDs individually. But what if you want to apply the **exact same set of styles** to multiple, different selectors?
- For example, you might want all of your headings (``, ``) and a specific class (`.note`) to have the same font and color. Writing a separate rule for each one would be repetitive and inefficient.
- This is where **grouping selectors** comes in. It's a fundamental technique in CSS that allows you to apply a single set of styles to multiple selectors at once, saving you time and making your code cleaner.

---
**Syntax**
- To group selectors, you simply separate them with a **comma (`,`)**. You can group any type of selector together: element selectors, class selectors, ID selectors, or a combination of them.

**Without Grouping (Repetitive)**

```css
h1 {
  font-family: 'Times New Roman', serif;
  color: #333;
}

h2 {
  font-family: 'Times New Roman', serif;
  color: #333;
}

.special-text {
  font-family: 'Times New Roman', serif;
  color: #333;
}
```
---
**With Grouping (Efficient)**

```css
h1, h2, .special-text {
  font-family: 'Times New Roman', serif;
  color: #333;
}
```

